The paper discusses the use of a particle-based model of slime mould to perform computational tasks such as statistical analysis and estimation. This suggests that the paper may belong to the sub-category of Multi-Agent Systems (cs.MA), which deals with the study of systems composed of multiple interacting agents. Additionally, the paper mentions the use of swarms of simple robotic devices, which further supports the possibility of it belonging to cs.MA. The paper also discusses the use of material adaptation and sensorial fusion, which are concepts commonly associated with Robotics (cs.RO) and Systems and Control (cs.SY). The paper's focus on approximation and tracking suggests that it may also belong to the sub-categories of Neural and Evolutionary Computing (cs.NE) and Artificial Intelligence (cs.AI), which deal with the study of computational models inspired by biological systems and the development of intelligent agents, respectively.
